ary includes all the step names plus start and end timestamps, and the grouping correctly resolves the user identity across the three possible ID sources.\n\nThe test description mentions the full coalesce expression, but that's actually defined in the SELECT clause as an alias, so the GROUP BY can just reference `resolved_id` by name. Moving on to how `queryFunnel` should work—the mock data returns rows with a level field indicating which step was reached.\n\nSince `windowFunnel` returns the maximum level each user achieved, I need to compute cumulative counts where step N includes all users who reached level N or higher. So for step 1, I'd sum the counts across all levels, for step 2 I'd sum levels 2 and above, and so on.\n\nThe test expects `{ steps: [] }` specifically when ClickHouse returns no rows at all, so I'll handle that empty result case.\n\nNow I need to handle the type coercion test—ClickHouse sometimes returns numeric values as strings depending on the output format, so I'll need to convert those to actual numbers.\n\nFor the route handler itself, I'm using Next.js App Router conventions where POST requests parse the body with `request.json()`.\n\nWriting the test file and implementation... Writing test cases... Writing test cases... Writing test cases... Writing test cases... Writing test cases... Writing test assertions...\n\nI need to handle the division by zero case when the previous step has zero users. For the string coercion test, the mock returns string values for both level and cnt, so I'm converting them with `Number()`. When tracing through a scenario with only levels 1 and 2 in the data, step 3 would correctly return 0 users since no rows exist for that level.\n\nNow I'm looking at the route test that expects a 400 response for invalid JSON. In Next.js App Router, `request.json()` throws an error when the body isn't valid JSON, so I need to wrap the parsing in a try-catch block to handle that case properly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":n